page.text: The University of Central Florida (UCF), located in eastern Orange County near the intersection of SR
434 (Alafaya Trail) and University Boulevard, is currently the second largest university in Florida and
the ninth largest in the nation with an enrollment of over UCF currently has over 42,000 students and
has recently completed the 2000 Campus Master Plan (CMP) Update. As a part of that update,
numerous capital projects were approved including the entire development program for the Wayne
Densch Athletic Complex except for the newly proposed football stadium that was recently added as a
proposed minor amendment to the 2000 CMP.
UCF is also one of the fastest growing universities in the U.S. with a projected total student population
of approximately 50,000 students. UCF is the also the home of the Golden Knights NCAA Division I
football team. The Knights recently joined the Mid-American college Football Conference.
In order to improve the standing of UCF’s athletics program, the University has embarked on a major
investment in athletic facilities on-campus. The Wayne Densch Athletic Sports Complex is a major new
mixed-use project planned for the northern end of the University of Central Florida (UCF) Orlando Main
Campus. This project is part of UCF’s plan to remain competitive at the highest level of the National
Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division I. UCF’s Athletics Department has identified the
provision of top-notch facilities to the student athletes as one of the key factors in recruiting and
retaining top athletic talent. The inclusion of these facilities on UCF’s Campus is also important to non-
athletes as they are a key aspect of the overall “college experience” and provide entertainment and
The purpose of the study is to first of all to evaluate the impacts of the proposed Wayne Densch
Athletic Sports Complex on the UCF and surrounding roadway network, including an evaluation of
parking demands. This analysis will be undertaken for two scenarios, i.e., the Base, approved, 2000
Campus Master Plan (CMP) and the revised plan including the football stadium.
The second part of the study will determine the parking demands that will be created by attendees and
users of the Complex, for both of the scenarios noted above. This part of the study will also examine
the existing and projected supply of parking facilities in the area that will be available to meet the
needs of both existing facilities and the planned Athletic Complex. Similar to the traffic impact
analysis, the parking analysis will also examine both scenarios described above.
The study area for the analysis was generally defined as the same one used for UCF’s Campus Master
Plan. Referred to in that document as the context area, it is generally bounded by SR 50 (Colonial
Drive) to the south, Chapman road to the north, Rouse Road to the west, and Lake Pickett Road to the
The results of the 2005 existing conditions analyses shows that the majority of roadway segments
within the study area are currently operating above the adopted Level Of Service (LOS) during weekday
conditions, with the exception of the following:
SR 50 (Colonial Drive) from Rouse Road to SR 434 (Alafaya Trail)
SR 50 (Colonial Drive) from SR 434 (Alafaya Trail) to Woodbury Road
Discovery Drive from Research Parkway to Gemini Boulevard
Lake Pickett Road from SR 50 (Colonial Drive) to Percival Road
Rouse Road from SR 50 (Colonial Drive) to Lokonatosa Trail
University Boulevard from Dean Road to Rouse Road
In addition to the evaluation of roadway LOS, the existing conditions assessment also determined that
UCF currently has 13,614 on-campus parking spaces in both surface and structured facilities. These
facilities are generally near capacity during normal business hours during weekdays. There is
significant available capacities on the weekend as UCF currently does not schedule and weekend
The analysis of the transportation related impacts of the proposed Athletic Center was separated into
two sections. The first section concerns the evaluation of the more “standard” land uses such as the
office space, convocation center, residential units (student housing), support retail space and the
smaller athletic venues. Since these uses will generally operate on weekdays during standard hours,
they were analyzed using “standard” traffic impact analysis practices and peak periods. Specifically,
traffic analyses for these uses examined weekday impacts during morning and evening peak periods,
generally recognized as 7-9 a.m. for morning peak and 4-6 p.m. for the evening peak period.
The second section focused solely on the projected impacts from the stadium. As currently planned,
the football stadium would hold six to seven football games per year, predominantly on Saturdays
during the fall semester. Most games are expected to start in the afternoon or early evening, generally
In general, the stadium analysis will closely conform to the methodologies outlined in two key
publications, “Managing Travel for Planned Special Events”, by Federal Highway Administration
(FHWA), published in 2003; and, “Transportation Planning and Management for Special Events”,
Synthesis 309 by the National Cooperative Highway Research Program (NCHRP). The synthesis,
published in 2003 surveyed several large venues around the United States and has several case studies.
The FHWA Handbook has a detailed structure that outlines the approach to preparing a feasibility study
When analyzing the football stadium it is important to recognize that this is a “special generator” that
will not be impacting the surrounding roadway system during peak periods generally analyzed under
standard practices. As such, the standard methodologies are not appropriate, as they will not address
the actual impacts of the stadium. If the standard, weekday peak periods (7-9 a.m., and 4-6 p.m.)
were analyzed, the stadium would show essentially no impacts as it would not be in use. As such, a
different analysis period needed to be selected that would more appropriately evaluate the overall
impacts of the stadium. Yearly, semester and weekly analysis periods were considered for the
evaluation of the stadium traffic impacts. After reviewing other related studies, the available traffic
data and the projected operating characteristics of the stadium, a weekly analysis period was selected.
Once all of the data had been collected, and the trips associated with all of the projects included in
the Athletic Complex and football stadium had been generated and assigned, roadway capacity
analyses were performed for the two scenarios:
Under this scenario most of the surrounding roadway segments within the study area will operate at a
LOS similar to existing, background 2005 levels. Several roadway segments that were already projected
to be failing will further degrade in terms of delay and several other roadway segments also declined in
LOS. However none of the roadways that were not already failing will not operate at a LOS below the
Peak hour traffic volumes generated by the UCF Campus on Saturday’s increase substantially due to the
football stadium traffic. Among the nine studied roadway segments within the study area, six will be
failing with capacity deficiencies. Two of the six roadway segments are external roadways including
Alafaya Trail (SR 434) from Colonial Drive (SR 50) to Science Drive and University Boulevard from Rouse
Road to Alafaya Trail. Although no data was collected on University Boulevard from Dean Road, it will
also likely be near or at failure.
The other four roadways are within the UCF campus, and include Gemini Boulevard from University
Boulevard to Libra Drive (three segments), University Boulevard from Alafaya Trail to Gemini Boulevard
and Gemini Boulevard from Alafaya Trail to North Orion Road.
The primary scenario to be analyzed for future parking demand is a sold-out UCF home Football game
with 45,000 attendees. Utilizing the mode split, and average auto occupancy percentages developed in
the trip generation estimates for the stadium, an estimate of the number of vehicles by type was
calculated at just over 11,400 parking spaces are estimated to be required for a sold-out football
game. When this demand of 11,400 spaces is compared to the projected 14,681 parking spaces
calculated in the previous section, it appears that there is an overall surplus of approximately 3,200
spaces. The majority of these spaces will be within a 10-minute walk of the football stadium.
Although not directly related to the evaluation of the traffic impacts related to the proposed UCF
Campus modifications, the question of whether or not the addition of a 45,000-seat football stadium
constitutes a major amendment is an issue that needs to be addressed. As noted in Florida Statute,
1013.30, a major amendment to an approved campus master plan (CMP) is deemed to have occurred
(9) An amendment to a campus master plan must be reviewed and adopted under
subsections (6)-(8) if such amendment, alone or in conjunction with other
(a) Increase density or intensity of use of land on the campus by more than 10
(b) Decrease the amount of natural areas, open space, or buffers on the campus
(c) Rearrange land uses in a manner that will increase the impact of any
proposed campus development by more than 10 percent on a road or on
another public facility or service provided or maintained by the state, the
county, the host local government, or any affected local government.
This report will not address 1013.30 (9) (a) or (b) as they refer to non-transportation related analyses.
Examination of 1013.30 (9) shows that provision (c) is the only transportation-related condition that
applies. However, review of this condition reveals that there is not any significant direction within the
statue to determine exactly how someone is supposed to determine if a proposed campus development
will increase impacts, “…by more than 10 percent on a road or on another public facility or service
provided or maintained by the state, the county, the host local government, or any affected local
An evaluation of the projected impacts from the proposed football stadium under F.S. 1013.30 (9) (c)
was performed based on the following assumptions:
The football stadium is a “special generator”,
That up to seven home football games will beheld,
That the majority of home games will occur on Saturdays.
The results of the analysis clearly determined, even for a 65,000-attendee sold out home
game, the maximum overall percentage increase on any surrounding roadway is equal to
8.47% when analyzed on a weekly basis, therefore not exceeding the condition listed in F.S.
A review of the trip generation and level of service evaluations for the “standard” weekday and the
Saturday Football scenarios clearly shows that the weekday impacts from the Wayne Densch Athletic
Complex will not adversely impact the surrounding roadway network. However, the projected impacts
from a sold-out, 45,000-attendee game have significant impacts on the surrounding roadway network.
Even the additional capacity gained from reduced background traffic volumes are not sufficient to
offset the trip generation from the stadium site. As almost all of the roadway facilities within the study
area are constrained and will not likely be widened any further, alternative means of mitigating
It is therefore recommended that a Transportation Management Program (TMP) be developed that
includes several Traffic Demand Management (TDM) strategies for football game conditions. These
include but are not limited to:
Create a Local Traffic Stakeholder Group – As the planned stadium could have dramatic
impacts on the LOS of surrounding roadways, it is suggested that the University develop a
stakeholder group to plan for and mitigate traffic impacts. The creation of the group will need
to address stakeholder roles and responsibilities, who will led the group meeting schedules,
etc. The group should include, but is not limited to:
Owners of Surrounding Student Housing properties
Increase the Public Transit/Park-N-Ride Mode Share – The existing LYNX service in the area
is limited to three routes with very long headways. The University should determine the
feasibility of working with LYNX to dramatically increase transit to the on-campus transit
center as much as possible. This could also include the creation of specialized, “Golden Knight”
express bus routes from the downtown Orlando area as well as any other surrounding areas
(such as regional malls) determined to have a high concentration of attendees. This will require
a pre-game marketing effort as well as coordination with facility operators as game attendees
Pre-Trip Traveler Information Techniques – The University should investigate a wide range of
communication opportunities in order to modify driver behavior and mode choice. These
include but are not limited to:
Specialized Event and Venue Transportation Guide (incl. Parking)
One specific item that the University is already exploring is the use of directed parking
management. UCF has retained the services of Gameday Management, Inc., to develop a parking
management system that will also help to distribute football traffic to the surrounding roadway
Traffic Management Techniques – There are a wide variety of traffic management techniques
that should be evaluated for applicability to UCF Football game days. These include:
Modifications to existing signal timing patterns
Installation of additional traffic signals that would only operate on games days/special
Installation of special, adaptive signal systems such as the SCOOT System installed by
Orange County on I-Drive that can handle highly-variable traffic flows
Geometric modifications to existing roadways or intersections such as the addition of,
or expansion to turn lanes, etc.
Improve Bicycle Accommodation - The University already enjoys a fair amount of bicycle
mode share due to the campus amenities, extensive trail network and local weather conditions.
Increasing bicycle amenities in the vicinity of t he stadium as well as improving safe access to
the stadium through the use of dedicated bike trails should be evaluated. Secure bicycle
parking should be located close to the stadium entrance. Staffing should be provided to
Guide Signing Program- A combination of static and dynamic message signs are a crucial part
of controlling traffic flows in the vicinity of the stadium. However, in order to be truly
effective, drivers must be “captured” a sufficient distance from campus in order to allow them
to make route decisions. It is therefore recommended that the University partner with FDOT
and OOCEA to secure respective agency approval to locate temporary changeable message signs
(CMS) on surrounding roadway. It is also suggested that the University examine the potential
for the installation of other permanent CMS signs at strategic points around campus to control
Reversible Travel Lanes – As the existing UCF internal roadway system is limited to a
maximum of four lanes on the major ring road, Gemini Boulevard, additional studies should be
conducted to determine the potential to convert Gemini Boulevard to one-way operation so as
to effectively double the overall roadway capacity. This option will require that special
provisions be made for the UCF Shuttles that will be traversing the campus moving attendees
from distant parking facilities to the stadium area.
Post Game Activities – As one of the highest traffic peaks will occur after the game is over, one
innovative approach to spread out the departure traffic demand would be to hold some event that
would keep some of the attendees on campus for a period of at least an hour after the game’s

This project provides every sport and support unit in UCF Athletics with a new home and includes:
New baseball practice field and an
A new softball stadium and two new practice fields,
There is also an option being considered that would replace the tennis center, aquatics center and
amphitheater with a new football stadium. This stadium is envisioned to initially include 45,000 seats
with an option to expand to 65,000 seats at a future date. The planned softball practice fields would
be moved south of North Orion Boulevard near the football practice fields.
Currently, UCF’s Knights play all of their home football games at the Citrus Bowl, located on the
western side of downtown Orlando, just north of SR 408. The Citrus Bowl hosts all six of the Knight’s
home games with an average attendance during the 2004 football season of just under 20,000
attendees. As it currently stands, almost everyone attending the games has to drive to the Citrus Bowl
– a one-way distance of over 17 miles for UCF students, faculty, staff and football team. UCF is one of
only 20 out of a total of 117 NCAA Division I-A universities do not have a stadium on-campus. Building a
stadium on-campus would bring over 10,000 students within walking distance of UCF football games.

page.text: The first step in evaluating the impacts of the Athletic Complex is to determine the existing operating
conditions so that the net impact from the planned projects can be calculated. This is determined by
collecting recent traffic data and comparing it to the existing number of lanes, the type of roadway
(i.e., arterial vs. collector) and the maintaining agency’s adopted Level Of Service (LOS) Standard. In
general, the LOS service volumes adopted by the FDOT are used as a starting point by most agencies,
although many modify them to take into account local conditions. A copy of Table 4-7 from the FDOT
2002 Quality/Level Of Service Handbook is shown below as Figure 2-1.
This table serves as the basis for the service volumes used in this analysis. Since the available roadway
segment data that was collected ranged from 2003 to 2004, it was decided to grow all raw counts to
2005 and adjust for seasonal adjustment factors per the FDOT Quality/LOS Manual. All counts were
adjusted using an annual growth rate of 2.44% that was calculated from permanent FDOT Count
stations in the vicinity of the UCF Campus.
Intersections were evaluated using the existing laneage and the traffic volumes collected as noted
above. In order to establish the most conservative future conditions evaluations, existing signalized
intersections had their signal timing plans optimized by using SYNCHRO, v. 6.0. This methodology will
show the highest LOS conditions that are currently achievable at the study intersections.

As noted above, turning movement counts were performed in 2005 at key intersections within the
study and surrounding the UCF Campus. These counts were collected from 7-9 a.m. in the morning and
4-6 p.m. in the evening to coincide with generally accepted peak analysis periods. Intersection
analyses were performed using the Synchro v. 6.0 traffic analysis software.

The UCF Campus already has a significant supply of parking spaces in both surface and structured
facilities. Many of the current surface lots are termed “temporary” as it is understood that the
University will eventually converts some of these surface facilities to either structured parking or new
Based on the most recent parking occupancy study performed by UCF staff, the Campus has a total of
13,614 parking spaces broken out by use in Table 2-5. In general, most of these are near capacity
during standard work/school hours during the week, with occupancy rates ranging from a low of 45% to
highs approaching 100%. On Fridays and weekends most of the parking spaces are empty except for
those lots attached to on-campus housing. Figure 2-2 shows the location of existing campus parking
facilities and their maximum capacities. A copy of the most recent UCF Parking Occupancy Study,
dated September 2004, is included in Appendix C.

As noted in FHWA’s handbook for special events, the first step in the study process is the generation of

For the purposes of this study, trip generation was broken into three major categories; more
“standard” uses such as the East Athletics Building and the Athletics Administration Building which
conform more closely to applicable ITE trip rates, smaller athletic sites such as the baseball and
softball stadiums, and the Convocation Center and football stadium which are generally referred to as
Planned Special Events. In this case the Convocation Center and football stadium are referred to as
Recurring Events at a Permanent Venue. Each of these categories will be discussed in detail below.

facility is alumni of the university although students, parents, faculty, staff, the administration, and
the community at large will have the opportunity to attend events at the facility.
As can be determined from the descriptions of each of these facilities, each is oriented toward UCF
student-athletes, staff, and faculty. It is therefore assumed that there will be a very high rate of
internal capture, in some cases as high as 100% as some of these uses while not destinations in and of
themselves, are restricted to students, faculty and staff that are already on-campus for another
primary purpose and were therefore accounted for under a different category or land use.

In light of the characteristics of a discrete/recurring event at a permanent venue, special
considerations when planning such an event include:
Permanent venues located in urban areas usually have exclusive off-street parking to accommodate
capacity events, and good access exists between venue parking areas and freeway/arterial corridor
traffic flow routes serving the venue.
In metropolitan areas, permanent venues often feature high-capacity connections (e.g., transit) to
the transportation system serving the region.

text.b: Parking areas at many permanent venues exist immediately adjacent to the venue, creating a
more self-contained site traffic circulation and pedestrian access environment similar to other
major, permanent traffic generators (e.g., airports and regional shopping centers).

As noted above, some of the key considerations noted by FHWA that are most applicable to the UCF
Football Stadium include those bullets that are bolded above and that deal with tail-gaiting, general
admission tickets, parking location and the ability to improve mitigation of traffic and parking impacts
over time as event data is gathered by staff. This information is also relevant to events held at the
Convocation Center, although not as directly applicable as the Center will hold a wide variety of events
whereas the stadium will host primarily college football games.
One of the key aspects to take away from the FHWA data is that predicting and mitigating impacts
from the stadium will improve over time as staff and local agencies/authorities better understand the
magnitude of the impacts and “iron out the wrinkles” in their mitigation plans. The results of this first,
preliminary study should be considered the first iteration in what will be an on-going process as UCF
seeks to find the best methods of planning for future events at the stadium and Convocation Center.

Football games at a fixed location such as the proposed UCF Stadium, are generally referred to as
“recurring special events at a permanent venue.” This unique type of venue has many traffic and
transportation variables and factors that must be considered when planning for the six home games
currently envisioned. As noted in Joseph Guyton’s technical paper from the ITE library, some of the
most critical factors that must be considered include:
Acceptable exit time following the event,
Distribution of arrivals over time and by direction, and
Acceptable entry/exit rates for on-site parking.
As noted in FHWA’s “Managing Travel for Planned Special Events Handbook”, there are a wide variety
of other factors that also need to be evaluated when considering these types of repetitive special
events. Event time and duration defines whether the event features a specific main event start time,
likely to condense event patron arrival, or operates continuously throughout the day where patrons
Event location defines the characteristics of the venue(s) location and connection to the
Typically, fixed venues, such as stadiums or arenas, feature high-capacity parking areas
adjacent to the venue and good access to/from adjacent freeways and principal arterial
Temporary venues may lack these features, thus requiring the development of a detailed
Area type defines the scope of available transportation services, the characteristics of
background traffic traversing the area, and the various stakeholders that may become involved
in event planning and management. These characteristics influence the event operations
planning process and day-of-event travel management, yet significantly vary across rural,
Event market area defines the area from where event patrons originate and the scope of event
For example, the Summerfest music festival in downtown Milwaukee drew over one million
in attendance over eleven days in 2002. Demographic surveys indicated 56 percent of
Summerfest patrons lived in the four counties comprising the greater metropolitan
Milwaukee area, 22 percent of patrons lived in other areas of Wisconsin, and 22 percent of
patrons lived outside Wisconsin.(1) The event clearly had a regional/statewide market
Expected attendance defines the maximum, estimated number of event patrons.
Attendance estimates may include the anticipated number of VIPs, advance ticket holders,
patrons with an assigned parking pass, and patrons requiring special assistance.
With regard to sporting events, key components in estimating attendance involve home
team performance and visiting team attraction.
Games involving high-profile visiting teams or performers may sell-out far in advance of the
event, allowing stakeholders sufficient notice to take appropriate measures.
Attendance impacts traffic operations in the immediate vicinity of the event venue
depending on the access and parking capacity furnished at the venue.
Audience accommodation defines the potential to predict the number and origins of event-
generated trips in addition to the type of trip patrons may make to the venue.
Attendance at free events is hard to predict and may vary considerably based on weather
conditions and other factors on the day-of-event.
Events featuring advance ticket sales and reserved seating may decrease the number of
event patrons making a spur-of-the-moment decision to attend an event.
Event type defines the type of event that may be subject to special regulations and permit
requirements. The event type includes many of the previously defined characteristics of
planned special events that influence event-generated travel demand and level of impact on
the transportation system. Event planners may refer to event type when researching impacts
on travel caused by similar events.
